ABUJA  – Nigerian Investment Promotion Commission (NIPC) has said it is seeking amendment to its Act in conformity with present investment realities. Ms. Yewande Sadiku, Executive Secretary/Chief Executive Officer revealed this yesterday at an interactive session with newsmen in Abuja. Sadiku said the Commission had taken the Act establishing the Commission to the National Assembly for consideration and amendments. EXPOSED - HOW LAGOS DOCTOR DISCOVERED MAJOR REASONS WHY MOST WIVES NOW HEAVILY CHEATS ON THEIR HUSBANDS AND THE PERMANENT SECRET TO SEXUALLY SATISFYING THEIR WIVES. DON'T BE A VICTIM! It would be recalled that NIPC was established by the NIPC Act No.16 of 1995 to encourage, promote and coordinate all investments in Nigeria. The Commission has perpetual succession and a common seal, which is specially established, among other things, to co-ordinate, monitor, encourage and provide necessary assistance and guidance for the establishment and operation of enterprises in Nigeria. Lagos NIS Tasks OSGoF, SURCON, National Body On Existing Law Amendment Tranter IT Emerges Best IT Support Provider, ICT Company Of the Year The Commission is also to initiate and support measures which shall enhance the investment climate in Nigeria for both Nigerian and non-Nigerian investors as well as promote investments in and outside Nigeria through effective promotional means. Sadiku noted that Foreign Direct Investments (FDIs) in Nigeria are largely driven by government policies. Speaking on the proposed amendment of the Commission’s Act, she said, there are areas that the present Act cannot benefit without its modernisation. Her words: “The NIPC Act was enacted in 1995. “We have been engaging with the National Assembly to modernise the Act so that it will suit the current realities. “There are areas that the present Act cannot benefit without modernisation. The conversation is ongoing.” Commenting on the impact of COVID-19 to the Foreign Direct Investments, she pointed out the 